">8</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:77.95pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">2</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:94.85pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2013 (to date)</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:103.45pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">10</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:120pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">4</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:77.95pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">1</span></p></td></tr></table></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Since the Committee’s last meeting with the NMC (October 2012):</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have reviewed over 1900 final decisions from NMC fitness to practise panels under s29 of our legislation. This represents 63 per cent of our total caseload, while NMC registrants constitute 47 per cent of the total number of registered professionals subject to s29 review</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We held 10 case meetings, three of which concerned NMC cases. We appealed one NMC case</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We had planned to hold a fourth NMC case meeting but this was unable to proceed: the registrant was no longer on the register at the time of the meeting as their registration had lapsed. </span></li></ul><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The problem of lapsing registration while under s29 appeal is one we have encountered in other NMC cases and continues to pose a challenge to public protection. We drew the Committee’s attention to this issue when we gave oral evidence in July 2013.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> While some of the regulators the Authority oversees have the legal power to hold a registrant on their register until any Court appeal that has been lodged by the Authority has been concluded, this is not the situation across the sector. The NMC’s legal framework means that once a fitness to </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">practise hearing is concluded, the nurse may ‘lapse’ from the NMC’s register if they have not complied with the requirements for renewing their NMC registration, even if the Authority has lodged a Court appeal against the fitness to practise panel’s decision. We are in discussions with the Department of Health and the NMC about the most effective means of closing this gap in the legislation.</span></h2><h1 style="margin:20pt 0pt 12pt 35.45pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Proposals for assuring the continuing fitness to practise of nurses and midwives</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In September 2013 the NMC discussed proposals for a phased introduction of a revalidation scheme with its Council. The minutes of this meeting have yet to be published, but we understand that the Council have opted for a model based on Prep standards with third party feedback and audit of a sample of registrants, some random and some risk-based for the first phase. All registrants would be revalidated within a three-year period, at the point of renewal. The Council’s decision about the approach for phase two has not been publicised. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Our 2012 paper on continuing fitness to practise highlighted the need for these regulatory mechanisms to provide robust assurances where higher levels of risk were identified.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We were concerned on reading the NMC’s proposal that it lacks a robust evidence base in particular around risk. As highlighted in the Performance Review report and in our paper on continuing fitness to practise, we would like to see a risk profile of the register, to help readers understand how they developed the options put before their Council, and why the preferred option was seen to be most fit for purpose. It is likely that different groups on the NMC register present different types and levels of risk and it may be that a range of mechanisms, varying in the levels of assurance they provide, might enable them to focus more of their resources where the risk is greatest.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Given that the NMC does not seem to have established what levels of assurance are needed, it is not surprising that there is little in the Council paper on what assurance the model provides. We therefore cannot be clear what is meant by the statement from the Council Paper that the proposals enhance public protection to the ‘desired level’.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We would expect any continuing fitness to practise mechanisms to enhance public protection, uphold professional standards, and bolster public confidence in the profession and in regulation. As we highlighted above, the risks to public protection have not been identified, evaluated or quantified. Further questions arise in relation to the proposals’ ability to deliver all three purposes, as we feel they do not address the following scenarios:</span></h2><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The registrant fails to engage with revalidation</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The registrant engages but does not meet the standards</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Concerns about conduct and/or competence are identified and meet the threshold for referral to the fitness to practise process.</span></li></ol><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">How the NMC responds to these three scenarios will play a significant part in determining the extent to which the proposals can fulfil the three-fold purpose by:</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Striking off or remediating, as appropriate, professionals who are not fit to practise in order to protect the public, and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Consistently, transparently and fairly enforcing the professional codes to ensure that professional standards are upheld and public confidence is maintained.</span></li></ul><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The September 2013 proposals prompt a number of additional questions, the answers to which are likely to affect the system’s ability to fulfil its regulatory purpose efficiently and effectively:</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">What will be the criteria for revalidation? The content of the Code and standards and how they are applied as revalidation criteria will be crucial to the success of the scheme. As highlighted in our Performance Review, the NMC accepts that the current Prep standards are not fit for the purpose of assuring continuing fitness to practise</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Will all nurses and midwives be in a position to meet the requirements for appraisals as the main method of third party confirmation of continuing fitness to practise, practically speaking, regardless of where or how they are employed?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Why is the revalidation cycle three years when the GMC’s cycle, with a profession that is arguably of higher risk, is two years longer?</span></li></ul><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We intend to raise these concerns with the NMC in any public consultations it carries out on its proposals. The Committee may wish to explore the NMC’s plans in greater depth. </span></h2><h1 style="margin:20pt 0pt 12pt 35.45pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Reviewing and refreshing policies and procedures </span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Since the publication of the Strategic Review, the NMC has started to make a number of changes to the delivery of its regulatory functions. In fitness to practise, the NMC has adopted two new case management processes: </span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Consensual panel determinations involving parties agreeing a statement of facts, an admission that the registrant’s fitness to practise is impaired and a proposed sanction</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Voluntary removal from the register, whereby a nurse or midwife who admits that their fitness to practise is impaired and who does not intend to continue practising can apply to a fitness to practise panel to authorise their removal from the register without a full public hearing of the allegations against them. </span></li></ul><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We will review all consensual disposal decisions using our powers under Section 29 of the NHS Reform and Health Care Professions Act 2002. Our audit sample this year included a number of cases in which the voluntary removal process was followed. We will report on our findings in relation to the NMC’s process, compliance with this process, and the potential impact on public protection, upholding standards and maintaining public confidence in the profession and its regulation later this year.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In registration, the NMC reviewed its registration process for international applicants in February 2013 and discovered that it had been operating different systems for evaluating the training requirements for applicants from New Zealand, America, Canada and Australia compared to the system for evaluating the training requirements for applicants from other non-European Union countries. It also found that improvements were needed to its procedure for validating identity requirements. The NMC stopped processing these types of applications in February 2013 until the review was completed in April 2013. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">7.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The NMC has subsequently strengthened its requirements for document certification and ID checking, including requirements for stamps on third party documents. However, they note that this has slowed down the processing of applications. In addition, they are planning the imminent introduction of face to face ID checks with passport scanning, and are consulting on the introduction of a competence test to replace the adaptation programmes. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">7.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In next year’s Performance Review we will report on whether the NMC’s new approach to international registration has dealt with the concerns highlighted in the review. We hope it will demonstrate a more effective approach to processing applications from international registrants that is sufficiently robust, transparent and equitable to maintain public confidence and uphold professional standards. We will be interested to see how these initiatives perform in relation to our key concerns around managing risk and fulfilling regulatory purpose.</span></h2><h1 style="margin:20pt 0pt 12pt 35.45pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Governance, oversight and transparency </span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">8.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The NMC Council was reconstituted in May 2013, and we advised the Privy Council about the appointments processes adopted by the NMC to identify council members. Our advisory role is based on four principles: that the process to identify a council member (or Chair) is fair, transparent and open, inspires confidence and requires decisions to be made on evidence of a candidate’s merit for the role. We advised the Privy Council that, as it demonstrated these four principles, they could have confidence in the process adopted by the NMC. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">8.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We note that the current Chair was appointed directly by the Privy Council in 2012 and his term is due to end in March 2014. We would anticipate similar processes would commence soon to assure the appointment of the Chair of the Council after this date. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">8.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Interim Report of the 2012 Strategic Review highlighted our concern that there was an inconsistent level of public debate and scrutiny between public and private sessions of the Council. We recommended that ‘the Council should move into private session after meeting in public only to discuss matters that are genuinely confidential.’ </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">8.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Paragraph 5.4, above, discusses the problem of lapsing registration while under s29 appeal. In August 2013, we lodged an appeal against a particular NMC fitness to practise panel’s decision with the High Court. As the nurse was about to leave the register we also obtained a High Court Order extending their suspension and preventing the nurse from leaving the register until our appeal was heard. The judge made it clear that the High Court has the power to intervene to ensure that justice is done in situations where there is a gap in the law of this type.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">8.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In this context, and given the NMC’s stated desire to fulfil all the recommendations of the Strategic Review and to meet its ‘litmus test’ of public protection, we were surprised to learn that neither the Authority’s s29 appeal nor the High Court Order were discussed by Council at their public meeting in September 2013. This omission could call into question the Council’s ability to address key risks to the organisation, and may undermine wider confidence that stems from appropriate transparency and openness. The Committee may wish to explore this issue further with the NMC. </span></h2><h1 style="margin:20pt 0pt 12pt 35.45pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion </span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">9.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The NMC is part of a system that has responsibilities for the safety and fundamental quality of care within the health system. The Francis Inquiry highlighted the importance of a coordinated and collaborative regulatory system, and what can happen when this is absent. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">9.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In our view the challenge for the NMC to build and sustain confidence in its regulatory performance remains. The underlying themes of risk and purpose recur throughout our scrutiny of the organisation, in this paper, in our performance review and in other areas of the Authority’s oversight (for example, early stages of fitness to practise and appointments processes). While its response to the recommendations of the Strategic Review was positive, ultimately the NMC’s success depends upon effective turnaround of its performance so it meets all 24 Standards of Good Regulation. The Committee may wish to assure itself that the Council is maintaining careful vigilance over factors that could impact both those functions relating to the NMC’s core regulatory purpose and those relating to its governance and operations. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">9.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In the Strategic Review we concluded, ‘the NMC should be allowed time to understand the task and to implement change. It needs to set itself realistic targets but then be sure that it meets them to build confidence both inside and outside the organisation.’ Realistic targets are based on an appropriate and informed understanding of risk and of the challenge of fulfilling the organisation’s regulatory purpose. The Committee may wish to seek assurances from the NMC that it is facing current regulatory challenges armed with the information, evidence and analysis that will allow it to fulfil its regulatory purpose well.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 3pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:-12pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">Case meetings are internal panels held with our lawyer present where we decide whether or not a particular case meets the threshold for an appeal to the Courts in the public interest.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:-12pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">Health Committee</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt"> 2013. Oral Evidence from Professional Standards Authority for Health and Social Care. Q15</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:-12pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">CHRE, November 2012. An approach to assuring continuing fitness to practise based on right-touch regulation principles. Available at: http://www.professionalstandards.org.uk/library/document-detail?id=69393f02-d5a3-4ae0-a1bb-a7b437dc3485. We stressed that mechanisms for assuring the on-going fitness to practise of registrants should be based on an evaluation and quantification of the risks presented by the regulated professions. We urged regulators to develop ‘a clear understanding of what professionals do, and of the context in which they do it’ in order to understand and quantify the risks, and target their regulatory response.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:-12pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">The Council paper states that ‘it is anticipated that if a nurse or midwife is not able to revalidate, they will lapse from the register’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:-12pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">As above: ‘it is anticipated that if a nurse or midwife is not able to revalidate, they will lapse from the register’.</span></p></body></html>